The leather industry in Nigeria has been unproductive for many years, contributing almost nothing to the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and the country’s foreign reserves, the Minister of Science and Technology, Dr. Ogbonnaya Onu, has said. Dr. Onu, who disclosed this in Abuja during the National Leather and Leather Products Policy Implementation Plan Validation Workshop, added that the absence of value addition had prevented the industry from upgrading its regional, global, inter and intra trade competitiveness. Represented by the Minister of State in the ministry, Mohammed Abdullahi, Dr. Onu said the industry was capable of generating not less than $800m annually if necessary things were put in place. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY He said, “Nigerian leather industry tans between 40 to 50 million skins annually, hence it generates between $600m to $800m annually. It is believed to have the potential to increase the nation’s foreign earnings.” The Chairman of the National Steering Committee on Strategic Implementation Plan of Leather and Leather Products Policy, Eucharia Oparah, told the gathering that the leather industry had witnessed decline in its performance because of the absence of a sector-specific policy and its implementation plan.  FG’s leather policy will boost industrial growth -Minister Leather key to Nigeria’s GDP growth - Minister FG to make research industry-driven - Minister Dear Readers, Kindly take one minute (1) of your time to fill out this short question. This questionnaire is designed to sample readers' opinions regarding what the feel about Daily Trust newspaper advertisement; it is not intended to used for any purpose other than to improve the quality of our newspapers. Any information provided will therefore be treated as confidential.